Goal:

Using the data collected from existing customers, build a model that will help the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio.

Input variables: Bank client data:

  1. age: Continuous feature
  2. job: Type of job (management, technician, entrepreneur, blue-collar, etc.)
  3. marital: marital status (married, single, divorced)
  4. education: education level (primary, secondary, tertiary)
  5. default: has credit in default?
  6. housing: has housing loan?
  7. loan: has personal loan?
  8. balance in account Related to previous contact:
  9. contact: contact communication type
  10. month: last contact month of year
  11. day: last contact day of the month
  12. duration: last contact duration, in seconds* Other attributes:
  13. campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client
  14. pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (-1 tells us the person has not been contacted or contact period is beyond 900 days)
  15. previous: number of times the client has been contacted before for the last campaign to subscribe term deposit
  16. poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign Output variable (desired target):
  17. Target: Tell us has the client subscribed a term deposit. (Yes, No)

Insights:

  1. Almost all age customers are subscribing term deposit.
  2. cusomers who has low balance in accounts are more subscribing term deposit.
  3. the customer who are last contacted for less duration are more subscribing term deposit.
  4. campaign(number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client) with low value are more subscribing term deposit.(no. of contact < 3)
  5. pdays impact:if number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted is grater than 900 days or they have not contacted (from a previous campaign),they are subscribing term deposit.
  6. previous: if the client has not been contacted before (for the last campaign to subscribe term deposit) ,then they are more subscribing term deposit.

In [40]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, recall_score, precision_score, f1_score, roc_auc_score,accuracy_score

logreg = LogisticRegression(random_state=10)
logreg.fit(X_train, Y_train)                    # fit the model on train data

Y_predict = logreg.predict(X_test) 

print(logreg.score(X_train, Y_train))
print(logreg.score(X_test, Y_test))

cm=metrics.confusion_matrix(Y_test, Y_predict, labels=[0, 1])

df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["No","Yes"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ["No","Yes"]])
plt.figure(figsize = (7,5))
sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True ,fmt='g')
plt.ylabel('Observed')
plt.xlabel('Predicted')
plt.show()
    
print("Recall:",recall_score(Y_test,Y_predict))
print()
print("Precision:",precision_score(Y_test,Y_predict))
print()
print("F1 Score:",f1_score(Y_test,Y_predict))
print()
print("Roc Auc Score:",roc_auc_score(Y_test,Y_predict))

Conclusion:

Here we want to build a model that will help the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio.

So, in this case hit rate should be greater , hence recall is an important metric.

As we can see from the above dataframe it is clear that Adaboost classifier and Bagging classifier gives maximum recall value, with good F1 score. Because of data imbalance, we can not choose accuracy and F1 score, because it can mislead our analysis.

So, Adaboost classifier is the best model that we can choose. Duration is an important feature over here.

We can deploy the model for practical use, after achieving desired outcome. As here,we can predict which customer is going to subscribe term deposit. Customer who are contacted for large duration are more likely to subscribe term deposit.
